rest_of_day_open: The rest of the week seems like it will go pretty well. I am preparing to take a short trip, and I've got my packing list started. I have several religious activities planned, as well as plans to talk to some friends. There are pork chops to have for lunch tomorrow.
critical_positive: Conversation partner was able to take the conversational ball and move it along. There weren't too many awkward silences. We said some things of personal interest without being grossly revealing or inappropriate. My conversational partner kept a pleasant expression as we talked and seemed interested in what I had to say, and had interesting things to say.
critical_negative: There were a few awkward topic transitions where we didn't know what to talk about next. I'm not sure we moved the spotlight of conversation back and forth as much as we should have, it felt like I dominated the conversation a little bit too much. Did not introduce ourselves, which is a little bit weird.

rest_of_day_open: I have to donate plasma, so I should feel good for the weekend. I'll feel good because I did something giving for my community. As long as work goes by smoothly, I should feel content for the rest of the day. After this study, I'm inclined to be a extra chatty at work
critical_positive: We were both females and seemed around the same age so that was welcoming. She had a very kind voice and seemed easy to talk to. We mostly talked about TV, work, and covid. Because I sensed that we were close in age it seemed easier to talk to her.
critical_negative: The whole conversation was very fluid, we didn't have any issues. There was a short moment of pause in the middle, but she had good follow-up questions. I think those awkward few seconds are always inevitable when you meet someone for the rest time. It would be interesting if we were instructed on specific questions to ask
